>>>>>>> # How can I reduce my risk of type 2 diabetes?
>>>>>>> ### You've just found out that you're at risk of developing type 2
>>>>>>> That's the really good news. It means that you now have the chance to
make changes that can delay or prevent type 2 diabetes. On this page you will
>>>>>>>> More than half of all cases of type 2 diabetes could be prevented or
>>>>>>> Take action now and it will make all the difference to your health in
>>>>>>> You can reduce your risk of developing type 2 diabetes by:
>>>>>>> * getting support to lose weight if you need to.
>>>>>>> Simple, right? We know it's not that simple and we're here to help you
get started. Most people know they need to make changes, but what can be
difficult is knowing how to do it – especially long-lasting changes.
>>>>>>> Remember, if you enjoy something, you're more likely to stick to it.
>>>>>>> Here are some tips to get you inspired:
>>>>>>> * Don't forget, you're not alone in this - there's lots of
>>>>>>> * Set goals which are realistic and work for you.
>>>>>>> * Change one thing at a time and make the changes part of
>>>>>>>> "I've always felt diabetes was inevitable for me and I'm learning
that I have a say in this by the lifestyle choices I make. My goal is to
fundraise and help Diabetes UK help others realise the same, so I started by
>>>>>>>> Tracy, who has a family history of type 2 diabetes
>>>>>>> Make the most of all the support and services available in your area.
>>>>>>> * a weight-loss programme or group - use our Know Your Risk
tool to find out if you're eligible for a place on the Diabetes Prevention
>>>>>>> * a registered dietitian or exercise specialist
>>>>>>> * a type 2 diabetes prevention programme
>>>>>>> * other local services to help you move more and eat better.
>>>>>>> It can also help to talk to family and friends – ask them to get
involved too. It will help if they understand what you're doing and why it's
so important. Plus, eating better and moving more is good for everyone, so you
>>>>>>> We're here to help too, with lots of tools and stories to keep you
motivated. Think about sharing your story – it could really help motivate
others. And remember, the trained counsellors on our helpline are ready to
support you if you have questions or just need a chat.
>>>>>>> Like everything in life, you'll have good days and bad days, but don't
>>>>>>> Set yourself realistic goals that fit in with how you live your life.
Choose the healthy food and activities that you like best. This will really
>>>>>>> And think ahead about anything that could stop you from achieving your
goal, and plan how you could overcome this.
>>>>>>>> "I keep a daily diary and log my weight and activity. It keeps me
>>>>>>>> Edward Morrison, who lost over four stone - read his story.
>>>>>>> You can download My weight-loss planner (PDF, 534KB) to set goals and
track your progress. By putting a plan in place and noting down your progress,
you'll be able to see the positive changes you're making.
>>>>>>> ## Make changes part of your everyday
>>>>>>> Changing too many things at the same time can make them difficult to
stick to in the long run. Start with small things you can change about your
>>>>>>> We know it can be hard to stay motivated, but remember you're in this
for the long run. Your risk of developing diabetes is serious and you can't
reduce your risk by eating better or moving more for just a couple of weeks.
>>>>>>> By building healthy meals into family life and moving more to help you
get from A to B, you can maintain these changes and look forward to a healthy
>>>>>>> Get 10 tips on how to eat well
